  "prompt": "I just passed BE mechanical and I am having a real hard time finding a job in core. Is it natural to happen so?",
  "response": "Yes, it's quite natural to face challenges when searching for a job in the core mechanical engineering field, especially right after graduating. Here are some reasons why this might be happening and what you can do about it:\n\n### **Why is it happening?**\n1. **High Competition**: Mechanical engineering is a popular field, and there are many graduates competing for limited core roles.\n2. **Lack of Experience**: Companies often prefer candidates with practical experience, which fresh graduates may lack.\n3. **Industry Shifts**: Some core mechanical industries (e.g., manufacturing, automotive) may be slow-growing or saturated in certain regions.\n4. **Skill Mismatch**: The curriculum may not align perfectly with industry requirements, especially in emerging areas like automation, robotics, or renewable energy.\n5. **Location Constraints**: Core mechanical jobs may be concentrated in specific industrial hubs, limiting opportunities in other areas.\n\n### **What Can You Do?**\n1. **Upskill Yourself**: Learn industry-relevant skills like CAD software (SolidWorks, CATIA), Finite Element Analysis (FEA), Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD), or programming (Python, MATLAB). Knowledge of emerging areas like IoT, Industry 4.0, or renewable energy can also make you stand out.\n   \n2. **Internships/Projects**: Gain practical experience through internships, freelance projects, or working on personal projects. This will make your resume more attractive.\n\n3. **Networking**: Attend industry conferences, seminars, and workshops. Connect with alumni, professors, and professionals on LinkedIn to explore hidden job opportunities.\n\n4. **Expand Your Search**: Look beyond traditional mechanical roles. Consider adjacent fields like HVAC, energy, robotics, or maintenance engineering.\n\n5. **Certifications**: Obtain certifications in areas like Six Sigma, lean manufacturing, or project management to enhance your profile.\n\n6. **Consider Further Studies**: If you're passionate about core mechanical engineering, pursuing higher studies (e.g., MTech or specialized courses) can open up more opportunities.\n\n7. **Be Flexible**: Be open to relocation or starting with entry-level positions to gain experience.\n\n### **Stay Positive**\nFinding a job can take time, and setbacks are part of the process. Stay persistent, keep improving your skills, and remain open to opportunities. Many engineers eventually find their niche, even if it takes a little longer than expected.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
